<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="div1" xml:id="midiGuidelines" n="0">
  <head>MIDI</head>
  <p>This chapter describes the basic MIDI encoding functionality present in MEI. The purpose of
    this module is to allow for integrating MIDI data into MEI-encoded notation, to both aid
    software in translating MEI to MIDI, and to permit the capture of information in files that have
    been translated from MIDI to MEI. The MIDI model in MEI is similar to that in Mup, and the user
    is directed to the <ref target="http://www.arkkra.com/doc/uguide.ps">Mup User Guide</ref> for
    further reading.</p>
  <p>The MIDI module defines certain generally-accepted MIDI units that may be used outside of a
    MIDI context. For example, the <att>dur.ges</att> attribute accepts MIDI <abbr>ppq</abbr>
    (Pulses Per Quarter) as a valid measurement of duration. Similarly, the <att>pnum</att>
    attribute allows MIDI note numbers for specifying a pitch value.</p>
  <div type="div2" xml:id="midiExamples">
    <head>MIDI Encoding Examples</head>
    <div type="div3" xml:id="midi.scoreDefppq">
      <head>PPQ in scoreDef and staffDef</head>
      <p>To define the MIDI resolution of a score, the <att>ppq</att> attribute may be used on the
          <gi>scoreDef</gi> and <gi>staffDef</gi> elements. This may then be used in conjunction
        with the <att>dur.ges</att> attribute on elements in the <ident type="class"
          >att.duration.performed</ident> class.</p>
      <p>
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
          <scoreDef meter.count="4" meter.unit="4" meter.sym="common" key.sig="1f" ppq="48">
            <staffGrp>
              <staffDef n="1" xml:id="midi.P1" lines="5" clef.line="2" clef.shape="G" key.sig="1f"/>
              <staffDef n="2" xml:id="midi.P2" lines="5" clef.line="4" clef.shape="F" key.sig="1f"/>
              <staffDef n="3" xml:id="midi.P3" lines="5" clef.line="4" clef.shape="F" key.sig="1f"/>
            </staffGrp>
          </scoreDef>
          <!-- snip -->
          <note xml:id="midi.d1e40" pname="a" oct="5" dur="8" dur.ges="24" stem.dir="up"/>
          <rest xml:id="midi.d1e58" dur="32" dur.ges="6" vo="4"/>
          <!-- snip -->
        </egXML>
      </p>
      <p>The <att>ppq</att> attribute is also available on the <gi>staffDef</gi> element in order to
        aid in the conversion to MEI of other representations that allow different time base data
        for each staff. However, these independent values for <att>ppq</att> are only interpretable
        in terms of a common time base. In the following example, the values of the <att>ppq</att>
        attribute are all factors of the <att>ppq</att> value given attached to <gi>scoreDef</gi>.
        Therefore, the <att>ppq</att> attribute is required when the values of <att>ppq</att> on the
        staff definitions differ.</p>
      <p>
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
          <scoreDef meter.count="4" meter.unit="4" meter.sym="common" key.sig="1f" ppq="48">
            <staffGrp>
              <staffDef n="1" xml:id="midi.P1" lines="5" clef.line="2" clef.shape="G" key.sig="1f"
                ppq="2"/>
              <staffDef n="2" xml:id="midi.P2" lines="5" clef.line="4" clef.shape="F" key.sig="1f"
                ppq="4"/>
              <staffDef n="3" xml:id="midi.P3" lines="5" clef.line="4" clef.shape="F" key.sig="1f"
                ppq="24"/>
            </staffGrp>
          </scoreDef>
        </egXML>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div type="div3" xml:id="midiInstruments">
      <head>Recording General MIDI Instrumentation</head>
      <p> The <gi>instrDef</gi> element can be used to record General MIDI instrument names using
        the <att>midi.instrnum</att> and <att>midi.instrname</att> attributes. These must contain
        values that are valid MIDI: 0-127 for <att>midi.instrnum</att>, or an instrument name from
        the list provided by the data.MIDINAMES data type.</p>
      <p>
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
          <scoreDef meter.count="4" meter.unit="4" meter.sym="common" key.sig="1f" ppq="48">
            <staffgrp>
              <staffDef n="1" xml:id="midi.P5" lines="5" clef.line="2" clef.shape="G">
                <instrDef midi.instrname="Violin" midi.instrnum="41"/>
              </staffDef>
              <staffDef n="2" xml:id="midi.P6" lines="5" clef.line="2" clef.shape="G">
                <instrDef midi.instrname="Violin" midi.instrnum="41"/>
              </staffDef>
              <staffDef n="3" xml:id="midi.P7" lines="5" clef.line="3" clef.shape="C">
                <instrDef midi.instrname="Viola" midi.instrnum="42"/>
              </staffDef>
              <staffDef n="3" xml:id="midi.P8" lines="5" clef.line="4" clef.shape="F">
                <instrDef midi.instrname="Cello" midi.instrnum="43"/>
              </staffDef>
            </staffgrp>
          </scoreDef>
        </egXML>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div type="div3" xml:id="midiData">
      <head>Recording MIDI event data</head>
      <p> In earlier versions of MEI, the <gi>noteOn</gi> and <gi>noteOff</gi> elements were used to
        record MIDI note on/off events. The use of these elements is now discouraged in favour of
        using the <gi>note</gi> element directly. MIDI timing duration should be recorded using the
          <att>dur.ges</att> attribute, and MIDI pitch information should be recorded using the
          <att>pnum</att> attribute. <hi><!-- this is only true if Issue #90 is fixed -->Velocity
          information should be recorded using the <att>vel</att> attribute.</hi>
      </p>
      <p> Most MIDI messages are encapsulated in the <gi>midi</gi> element, and is typically used in
        contexts like <gi>layer</gi> and <gi>measure</gi>. MIDI events like Control Changes
          (<gi>cc</gi>) are simply encoded using the <att>num</att> and <att>val</att> attributes.
        Control change numbers are specified in the General MIDI documentation. In the example
        below, the CC element encodes controller event 7 (Volume) with increasing values from 50 to
        65 specifying the MIDI volume value. </p>
      <p>
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
          <measure>
            <staff>
              <layer>
                <midi>
                  <cc num="7" val="50"/>
                </midi>
                <note pnum="42" dur.ges="8"/>
                <midi>
                  <cc num="7" val="55"/>
                </midi>
                <note pnum="43" dur.ges="8"/>
                <midi>
                  <cc num="7" val="60"/>
                </midi>
                <note pnum="44" dur.ges="8"/>
                <midi>
                  <cc num="7" val="65"/>
                </midi>
                <note pnum="45" dur.ges="8"/>
              </layer>
            </staff>
          </measure>
        </egXML>
      </p>
      <p> Most other MIDI event messages follow this same pattern, using the <att>num</att> and
          <att>val</att> attributes to record the raw MIDI data. </p>
    </div>
  </div>
